<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06186086 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06186086 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FREMONT; END; MEDICAL; SERVICE; TAX  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A proposed 142 percent increase in the Fremont emergency medical services taxhas been junked for at least a year -- and maybe for good.;    Citingconfusion over information in a staff report, the city council voted earlyWednesday morning to reconsider its week-old recommendation to raise theparamedic tax from $19 to $46.05 a year, which would have given Fremont thehighest rate in Alameda County.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FREMONT KILLS MEDICAL-SERVICE TAX -- FORNOW  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Three-week recess;  The decision to reconsider means the increase is deadfor one year because the council is on a three-week recess and won't meetagain until Aug. 6. The Alameda County Board of Supervisors, which mustapprove the rate hike, will only be considering proposed increases inmid-July.;    &quot;There wouldn't be another change possible until next year,&quot;said Ben Mathews, the county director of emergency medical services.;   Mathews told Fremont officials that he opposed the increase because the cityplanned to use the money for firefighter salaries, which is against countypolicy.;    The 142 percent increase would have generated about $2 million tofinance the program and pay portions of the salaries of the 38paramedic-trained firefighters -- freeing up $2 million in city general fundmoney at a time when the city is facing a serious budget crunch.;    Taxpayersprotest;  But several council members received letters and phone callsprotesting the increase. And they apparently thought the $2 millionrepresented the cost of the fire department's paramedic program -- not asalary savings.;    Mayor Bill Ball was the lone dissenter in the decision toreconsider.;    In other action, the council:;    (check) Approved using abuilding at 39550 Liberty St. for city offices. It also authorized the citymanager to negotiate leases for additional office space. Council members GaryMello and Alane Loisel voted no. This space would replace City Hall officeswhich sit on the Hayward Fault.;    (check) Approved a November ballot measureasking voters if they want to switch the municipal elections from odd-numberedto even-numbered years and a second measure asking whether the election switchshould occur in 1992 or 1994. Ball and Councilman John Dutra voted no onboth.;    (check) Adopted a 90-day interim budget that continues spending atthe present level until the council can approve a final fiscal 1992 budget.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DENNIS AKIZUKI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910704  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  379  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday July 4, 199100186086,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>